The standard approach is to **wrap them behind an interface** and inject it:

```csharp
public interface IFileSystem
{
    string ReadAllText(string path);
    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);
    bool DirectoryExists(string path);
}

public class PhysicalFileSystem : IFileSystem
{
    public string ReadAllText(string path) => File.ReadAllText(path);
    public void WriteAllText(string path, string contents) => File.WriteAllText(path, contents);
    public bool DirectoryExists(string path) => Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

Then inject `IFileSystem` into classes that need it. In tests, mock it or use an in-memory implementation:

```csharp
public class InMemoryFileSystem : IFileSystem
{
    private readonly Dictionary<string, string> _files = new();
    private readonly HashSet<string> _dirs = new();

    public string ReadAllText(string path) =>
        _files.TryGetValue(path, out var c) ? c : throw new FileNotFoundException();
    public void WriteAllText(string path, string contents) => _files[path] = contents;
    public bool DirectoryExists(string path) => _dirs.Contains(path);

    public void AddDirectory(string path) => _dirs.Add(path);
}
```

**Alternatively**, the NuGet package [`System.IO.Abstractions`](https://www.nuget.org/packages/System.IO.Abstractions) provides a ready-made `IFileSystem` that wraps the entire `System.IO` surface — saves you from maintaining your own interface as needs grow.
